3. ASSESSMENT OF THE MEASURE
The decision taken by SNCB/NMBS on 7 April 2003 to grant restructuring aid to IFB is attributable to the Belgian State, since the submission of the restructuring plan to it for approval, as well as articles published in the press, indicate that it influenced the decision. On the other hand, the Commission has doubts about whether the tacit granting of extensions for payments by SNCB/NMBS since 2001 at the earliest and 19 September 2002 at the latest is attributable to the Belgian State.
SNCB/NMBS has not behaved like a creditor (as regards the extension for payment), or like an informed investor in a market economy (as regards the remaining measures) given that the return on the capital invested is below what such an investor would have accepted.
The cash aid cannot be regarded as rescue aid since its duration exceeds twelve months.
For aid to be regarded as restructuring aid compatible with the common market, a firm must be eligible within the meaning of the restructuring guidelines and the aid has to satisfy five conditions:
(1) The restructuring plan must make it possible to restore the long-term viability of the firm within a reasonable period.
(2) Measures must be taken to mitigate, as far as possible, any adverse effects of the aid on competitors.
(3) The aid must be limited to the strict minimum needed to enable restructuring to be carried out, and the firm must make a contribution to its restructuring.
(4) The Commission must be able to satisfy itself, on the basis of regular detailed reports, that the restructuring plan is being implemented properly.
(5) The restructuring aid should be granted once only.
The Commission cannot at this stage rule out the possibility that IFB received part of the aid less than three years after it was set up. It therefore has doubts about whether IFB is eligible for the restructuring aid.
It emerges from the Commission's examination that criteria 1, 4 and 5 are met. However, the Commission has doubts about whether the measures taken to mitigate, as far as possible, any adverse effects of the aid on competitors are sufficient, and whether IFB's own contribution is sufficient.
With regard to mitigating adverse effects on competition: the Belgian authorities have indicated that IFB has taken the following two measures to mitigate, as far as possible, any adverse effects of the aid on competitors:
- it has virtually closed down its activities in France,
- in Belgium it has closed the Bressoux terminal and sold its shares in the terminals in Brussels and Zeebrugge.
These two measures reduced its turnover from EUR 62 million in 2002 to EUR 58 million in 2003. However, given that these measures appear to concern loss-making activities, the Commission has doubts about whether it can take them into account.
To determine whether these two measures are sufficient to mitigate, as far as possible, any adverse effects of the aid on competitors, it is necessary to take into consideration the main developments on the two markets on which IFB operates, namely the logistics market and the freight transhipment market. Subsequently, an analysis should be made of whether the measures proposed do mitigate, as far as possible, any adverse effects of the aid on competitors.
a) The logistics market and the aid for IFB
The logistics market is in a state of flux as a result of the opening-up of the rail transport markets and the entry of railway and postal undertakings on to the market, resulting in both a large number of small specialised operators and big integrated ones.
The Commission notes that the measures proposed do not concern the logistics market. IFB succeeded in increasing its volume on this market substantially in 2004 (compared with 2003). Belgium did not make any commitment which would have limited, at least temporarily, IFB's presence on this market.
The Commission therefore considers that the facts that no measures have been proposed concerning the logistics market, that the market is in a state of flux, and that IFB has succeeded in increasing its volume substantially raise doubts about whether Belgium has limited, as far as possible, any adverse effects on competition as far as IFB's logistics activities are concerned.
b) The freight transshipment market and the aid for IFB
The two measures proposed concern the freight transshipment market. IFB has virtually ceased its operations in France, and has closed one terminal in Belgium and sold its shares in two others.
Consequently, the Belgian market is the only one on which the aid may have adverse effects on competition. IFB has less than 7 % of this market.
To limit the adverse effects of the aid on the Belgian market, IFB has closed one terminal and sold its shares in two others. The Commission notes, however, that the smallest terminal was closed, that its closure was primarily intended to reduce the losses of IFB Terminals, and that, following the capital increase, IFB will once again be operating the two terminals which it sold, since SNCB/NMBS will transfer to IFB 47 % of its shares in TRW, which has major holdings in the Brussels and Zeebrugge terminals.
Moreover, TRW also operates many other terminals in Belgium. Consequently, the capital increase through the contribution in kind from TRW shares will have the effect of increasing IFB's share of the Belgian market.
The Commission further notes that IFB has minority holdings in a large number of Belgian terminals.
The Commission therefore has doubts about whether the measures proposed by IFB to limit, as far as possible, the adverse effects of the aid on competition on the transhipment market are sufficient.
With regard to IFB's own contribution: According to the information supplied by the Belgian Government, IFB does not itself appear to have contributed to its restructuring, as required by the 1999 and 2004 guidelines. The Commission therefore has doubts about whether IFB's own contribution is sufficient.
